Kadu’s Ronald Ngala considered regionalism key to "practical democracy", and demanded that full independence should come at a later date. Ngala particularly feared the domination of smaller tribes by larger tribes in Kanu. 

Because of Kadu’s fears, there were many detailed safeguards in the Majimbo constitution. A provision was made for an independent judiciary and an entrenched Bill of Rights. 

Constitutional changes had to get a 75 per cent majority in each House. But in the case of entrenched tribal or individual rights, it had to be 90 per cent in the upper house. 






Kanu leaders made concessions in the hope that they would get rid of them as soon as they formed internal self-government in June 1963. The suspicion and mistrust in the coalition government was evident as soon as the delegates returned to Nairobi in 1962. 

At Kariokor, Tom Mboya, in a jibe targeted at Kadu, said, “If two of you buy a car but one of you doesn’t know how to drive, he can’t ask the other one why he always drives the car. You must learn to drive first before you buy the car, that is why Kanu agreed to join the coalition government.” 

He also never hid his aim of eventually suppressing regionalism. 

 “We see our position in the future as based on consolidating and strengthening the central machinery,” he said. “With the support of the country we will be in a position to remove or amend any and all parts of the constitution which are unworkable, expensive or hinder general progress.” 



